ngs Pretty Kitty Kelly\n10:15 j Margo of Castlewood John's Other Wife (Traffic Court Myrt and Marge\n10:301Terry Regan, serial Just Plain Bill Get Thin to Musk Emily Post, etiquette\n10:45 Better Business Women in White Louis Rich (Music\u2014News\n11:00 Mary Marlin, serial David Harum, serial Louis Rich Mary let Taylor\n11:15 Popular Waltzes Backstage Wite Musical Potpourri Carol Kennedy\n11:30 Vic and Sade, serial Eleanor Howe (Big Sister, serial\n11:45 Edward MacHugh Jerry Brannon, songs Joan Meriill, songs Real Life Stories\nTmTI\n12:00 Thought Time News\u2014Header I Luncheon Music [Mary McBride\n12:15 News\u2014Music The 0 Neills, serial (News Bulletins :Your News Parade\n12:30(Farm enctHome Hour George Hall Orch. 'Church of the Air .Helen Trent, serial\n13:451 _Three Romeos, songs Vocal Varieties Our Gal Sunday\n1:00 Farm and Home Hour Emerson Gill's Orch. King's Jesters (Betty and Bob\n1:15 Escorts and Betty Mike in the Sky Hymn Program\n1:30 Mother-in-law Words and Music Rex Battle's Orch. Grimm\u2019s Daughter\n_ 1:45 Rakov's Orchestra _Voice of Experience Valiant Lady\n2:00 Rakov's Orchestra Fun in Music Wakeman's Sports ~WayneVan Dfne\n2:151Let s Talk It Over The O'Neills, serial\n2:30 Consumers' Program Mary Mason School of the Air\n2:45 Armchair Quartet\n3:00 U. S. Marine Band Pepper Young, serial News Bulletin! Aladdin's Kitchen\n3:151 Ma Perkins, serial Jean King, songs\n3:30: i Vic and Sade, serial Wakeman's Sports Cin innali Symphony\n3:45 _(Guiding Light, serial _\"\n4:00 Club Matinee Lorenzo Jones, serial Wakeman\u2019s Sports (Cincinnati Symphony\n4:15; Mary Marlin, serial Songland (Afternoon Rhythms\n4:30 Hughes Reel Wakeman's Sports Goldbergs, sketch\n4:4r I_Sundown Revue_: Linda s First Love\n5:001 Evening Star Flashes Dick Tracy, serial Lawrence Salerno, org.! Follow Moon, serial\n5:15 |Tea Time Terry and Pirates Harold Turner, piano Mary Sothern, serial\n5:30 Singing Lady Jack Armstrong Cocktail Capers Stepmother, serial\n5:45 .Torn Mix, serial ;Little Orphan Annie (Hilltop House, serial\nWild Bison Still\nLive in Canada\nThis toeek has been designated by\npresidential proclamation as Na\ntional Wild Life Week. Chief ac\ntivity of the week will be sale of the\n\"Ding\u201d Darling series of wild life\nstamps. Mr. Darling, former head\nof the Biological Survey, has writ\nten a series of sketches about the\nanimals whose pictures appear on\nthe stamps. This is No. IS.\nBy \u201cDING'\u2019 DARLING.\nOur buffalo, the American bison, is\nforever gone In its old abundance.\nThe thundering herds of millions,\n\u2022weeping from the Canadian prairies\nto the Gulf of Mexico and back in\ntheir search for fat grazing lands,\ncould not now be tolerated in a coun\ntry of railroads, towns, fences and\nfarms.\nThere are many men now living\nwho can recall the last of the vast\nherds. Bison vanished east of the\nMississippi about 1800, but the last\nwild specimens were killed in the West\nless than 50 years ago. Sixty years\nago, at Kearney, Nebr., there was\na factory for canning buffalo tongues.\nBuffalo robes were the standard equip\nment for every one who owned a horse\nand buggy. Bales of raw buffalo hides\n\u25a0old at 4 cents a pound.\nFrom the buffalo the Indians got\nfood, clothing and shelter, the hides\nbeing used in making tepees. Hunted\nwith arrows and lances, the enormous\nherds were never seriously affected\nbefore the coming of the white man.\nGreat lobo wolves followed the buffalo\nas they moved up and down the\ncountry and destroyed the weak and old.\nThe white man made short work\nof this great natural endowment. As\nsoon as a slight profit was discovered\nin the mass slaughter the leather\nmarkets of the world were glutted\nwith the cheap hides from the Ameri\ncan bison and every farmer who\nwanted one could afford a buffalo\novercoat.\nThere was little enough sport in\nbuffalo hunting, and at times the\nplains were strewn with the rotting\ncarcasses of splendid animals, killed\nfor their hides alone.\nThe American Bison Society has\nmade a close study of the history of\nthe bufTalo. It is estimated that in\n1870 the surviving herds numbered\nabout 14,000.000. The last census of\nbison, in 1929, gave 3.385 animals at\nlarge in the United States\u2014living\nwithin tile protection of national parks\nand Unted States Biological Survey\nrefuges. It is estimated there are\n14,909 in Canada.\nIt is not generally known that bison\nin its wild state never did become\nentirely extinct. There remains a\nherd of the original woods bison near\nGreat Slave lake, perhaps 200 or 300,\nrarely seen by white men.\nANNUAL MEETING SET\nThe Monday Evening Club will hold\nits annual dinner meeting tonight at 7\no'clock at the Y. W. C. A., with Karl\nde Schweintz, director of the Penn\nsylvania School of Social Work, as\nthe principal speaker. He will talk\non \u201cWhy Public Welfare?\u201d\nWilliam A. Roberts, president of\nthe club, will introduce the speaker.\nMaurice V. Brooks is chairman of the\nCommittee on Arrangements. Res\nervations for the dinner were limited\nto 190 persons.\n50\u00b0 SERVICE 50\u00b0\nAll Makes Repaired\nPHONE 8 A.M. TO 8 P.M.\nLEtTH BROS.\n\u25a0220 13th St M W MCt 07*4\nBOAKE\nCARTER\nNOW ON\nNEW TIME\n6:30\nWJSV\nfcy N\u00bbt TwiBw mi IlmMu\nU. a WAR STATUS\nIS TOPIC TONIGHT\nMcReynolds Will Discuss\nWorld Situation in\nForum at 10:30.\nWith the news headlines daily\nshouting of turbulence abroad and\nhinting that perhaps the Atlantic\nOcean and the Pacific Ocean are not\nas big as we\u2019ve always thought them\nto be, Representative McReynolds of\nTennessee comes before the National\nRadio Forum tonight to discuss a\nquestion that is on almost every mind\nin the country today\u2014\"Are We Build\ning for Peace or War?\u201d\nIt is expected that Mr. McReynolds,\nwho is chairman of the House For\neign Affairs Committee, will discuss\nthe position of this country with ref\nerence to the tangled affairs of Eu\nrope and the strife in China. He also\nwill touch upon the country's national\ndefense program as it is exemplified\nin the administration\u2019s new naval\nbuilding program.\nThe Radio Forum, arranged by The\nStar, is broadcast over a Nation-wide\nchain of National Broadcasting Co.\nstations and reaches local listeners\nthrough the facilities of WMAL at\n10:30.\nThis, the first day of spring, brings\nto the air waves a group of outstand\ning business leaders, who will provide\nfirst-hand discussions on the \u201cSpring\nOutlook on Business\" (WRC at 9:30),\nT. M. Oirdler, president of the\nAmerican Iron and Steel Institute,\nwill represent his industry; Joseph\nSchenck, president of the Motion Pic\nture Producers Association, will be\nheard on the movie outlook; automo\nbiles and petroleum, closely linked, will\nbe represented by Alvin Macauley,\npresident of the American Automobile\nManufacturers Association, and A. J.\nByles, president of the American\nPetroleum Institute.\nOther speakers and their fields of\nendeavor include: J. J. Peliey, trans\nportation; Paul S. Willis, the con\nsumer field; Dr. John P. Anderson,\ndrug manufacturing; Morris W. Haft,\nthe clothing industry, and Edwin S.\nFriendly, newspaper advertising.\n\u201cMarch Slav\u201d and Dvorak,\nThe Barrere-Salzedo-Britt Trio will\nassist the Eugene Ormandy-conducted\nPhiladelphia Orchestra on tonight's\nbroadcast CWMAL at 9). Georges\nBarrere, flautist, and Carlos Salsedo,\nharpist, will be heard with the or\nchestra in Mozart\u2019s \u201cConcerto for\nFlute and Harp with Orchestra, An\ndantino\u201d; Horace Britt, cellist, and\nMr. Salzedo will Join in Ravel's \u201cPiece\nen forme de Habanera,\u201d and the en\ntire trio will be heard in Ravel's\n\u201cMenuet and Finale from the Trio,\nSonatina.\u201d\nOther orchestral selections on the\nprogram will be Nicolai's overture to\n\u201cMerry Wives of Windsor.\u201d \u201cRhumba,\"\nby Harl McDonald; Dvorak's \u201cSlavonic\nDance No. 1 in C Major,\" and in con\nclusion, Tsrhaikowsky's \u201cMarch Fav.\"\nThe same \u201cMarch Slav\" and an\nother Slavonic dance by Dvorak, this\nNo. 8, will be played by Alfred Wal-\nlenatein\u2019a Symphonic brehestra (WRO\nat 8:30), On this program the or\nchestra will also be heard in the over\nture to Offenbach\u2019s \"Orpheus\u201d and\nTenor Richard Crooks will feature\n\u201cLe Reve,\u201d from Massenet's \u201cManon,\"\nAlso on Tonight.\nLupe Velez, Libby Holman. Clifton\nWebb, Toby Wing, Rex O\u2019Malley and\nApril (yes, that\u2019s right) will appear\non Dollie Slaughter\u2019s \"Back Stage\"\nbroadcast from the National (WJSV\nat 7:30), .They're the stars of the\nmusical, \"You Never Know,\u201d which\nopens tonight George Arliss makes\nanother of his infrequent radio ap\npearances, to play a leading role in\n\"The Man Who Played God,\u201d on the\nRadio Theater (WJSV at 9) Mme.\nMaria Kurenko\u2019s featured number on\nthe Contented Hour (WRC at 10)\nwill be Leoncavallo\u2019s \"Serenade.\u201d\nH. M.\n'Flood Retards Season.\nAUGU8TA, Ky. 14\u00bb).\u2014Augusta and\nMount Olivet High Schools will close\ntheir 1937\u2014that\u2019s right^-basket ball\nseason Saturday.\nThe game was to have been played\nlast year, but was washed out by the\nflood.\n>MILVERIv\nf/ce C RE.AW*\nMad\u2022 /o Matt High*tt\n1^^ Quality Standardt ^^k\nAmayUuf?\nM&, Mudim! 2bay Ajt&i 3>ay\nTHOITlflS GROWS HAIR\nYEARS ago the re-growth of hair on bald heads was\nunusual and amazing. Today, modern science in\nthe form of Thomas\u2019 reliable treatment has made re\ngrowing hair a routine matter\u2014a daily occurence. Each\nday The Thomas\u2019 are ending dandruff, stopping ab\nnormal hair-fall, and re-growing hair for more than\n1600 persons.\nWith Thomas\u2019 precise, modern method of retaining\nor regaining hair available there is no reason why you\nshould become bald or remain bald. If you do, you do\nso by choice. Baldness is not thrust upon you. It warns\nyou of its approach\u2014you have dandruff; your scalp\nitches; your hair falls abnormally. You douse your scalp\nwith cure-all concoctions and try hit-or-miss treatments\n\u2014and almost before you know it your scalp is ready\nto join a nudist colony.\nChoose hair not baldness. More than a quarter\nmillion other men have found that hair can be retained\nor regained by the reliable proved Thomas method.\nThomas can help you to get rid of your dandruff; stop\nfalling hair; ana re-grow hair on the thin and bald spots.\nConsult a Thomas expert today. He will examine your\nscalp without charge or obligation, and tell you frankly\njust what can be done in your particular case. He knows\nthe symptoms of the 14 local causes of baldness and\nknows exactly how to overcome them. Remember\u2014scalp\nexamination is free.\nThe tf,r*e Photographs at the right show 1\nhow Thomas treatment completely re-grew 1\nh.\u2018*40in\u00ab HAl* :A hair on bald spots for Mr. Wm. Eckhardt. I\nfi SCAlVWciAUSTS]_ i\n\u25a0L \"r, *o*t I,\nSUITE 1050-51, WASHINGTON BUILDING\nj^B (Corner N. Y. Avenue ond 15th St. N.W.) 1\nH (Separate lie pm tments for Men and Women) 1\nHOURS\u20149 A.M. to 7 P.M. SATURDAY' to 3:30 P.M.\n...THE PICTURESQUE EAST-WEST TRAVEL WAY\nWestward from bustling sea-ports of the Atlantic...through\nthe land of America\u2019s beginnings ...out to the Gateway Cities\nthat open on the great west...there lies THE CHESSIE COR\nRIDOR. And through this Corridor runs the Chesapeake and\nOhio\u2019s fine fleet of genuinely air-conditioned trains \u2014THE\nGEORGE WASHINGTON\u2014THE SPORTSMAN\u2014THE F. F. V.\nEastward or westward,The Chessie\nCorridor rewards the traveler with a wealth\nof varied scenic beauty and historic interest.\nIn the eastern end lies the storied ground\nwhere our nation was made free. Then, as\nyour air-conditioned train moves west, his\ntory unfolds another tremendous chapter\u2014\nthe struggle of the 1860s\u2014for you cross the\nvery fields where tides of battle flowed...\nWestward, through the Piedmont and Shen\nandoah Valleys and over the majestic Blue\nRidge Mountains between them...Over the\npicturesque Alleghanies, down through the\nmost thrilling canyon east of the Rockies\u2014\nthe New River Gorge...Then you follow the\ngreat winding Ohio River...the blue grass\nregion of Kentucky... on northward to the\nbeauty of the Great Lakes. Stimulating\nsights...comfortable riding...perfect content\nment... in whatever direction you travel The\nChessie Corridor...climaxed in a quiet sleep-\ning car that invites you to Sleep Like a Kitten.\n'\u2014yloryTZUadunyltmb /f&ulrotuf\nCHESAPEAKE w OHIO\n\nOryinaL^rtcltctAior (omptuuj OSi^1v (^eoryTT/JaAkuiyton. m 1785\nFor reservations or other information please communicate with\nF. E. LANOMEIER, D. P. A. 714 14TH STREET, N. W. PHONE NATIONAL Q821\nI PHILLIPS TOMATO JUICE\ntables of\nthose who Ihink of it! One of the biggest big ft\nknow\u201d nickel values we\u2019ve ever offered. 20-oz.\nEnough for the whole family. can\nUUHEATIES IQc\nOUR FAMOUS APRICOTS unk&d-\u2122 10c\nGjS?rNtl!G PIE CHERRIES_2\" 25c\nIf y Y r t t RIBBON BRAND SOUR\u2014Quality You Know\nNow at the lowest\nprice in history\u2014No\nchange in quality\nWhy pay wore unless\nyou get moref\n,i 20c\nWilkins Coffee 25c LIDO CLUB ^dinnI\u2122. pk* 21C\nSANICO CAKE FLOUR 0 pkg*- 20C I Smooth Texture I I\nRicher\u2014Sweeter\nNEW ENGLAND SYRUP _ ft 15c\nLAND O\u2019 LAKES cheese lb 29c\nRED HEART VIM PEP I\nDOG FEED DOG FEED d d c n n\n45* 98c o=ra j.\nl~a,gT---MllS\u201d-25. I\nFANCY, LOCALLY GROWN\nStayman Apples\nJust at the season when you'll want to JUMBO\ngive the children several apples a day. %g D D E A H\nAlso no better apple for cooking, pies, D It C A If\netc. Buy a large bag full at this ex- Each \u00b0ne pound Qc\ntremely low price_ sliced loaf -y\nFLORIDA tree-ripened R0Se Rushes Special eiuh 25c I\nD A D IT ET D III T IS THE TIME TO PLANT YOUR ROSE BUSHES\n1 ^B \u25a0M ^B III I Z* 3,pec\u2018al offering of fine, liealthv\nmJH BB ^^B B mmt I II I B rosebushes In ass